title: Grateful Dead Live at Boston Garden on 1977-05-07
description:
Set 1

Bertha, Cassidy, Deal, Jack Straw, Peggy-O, Minglewood Blues, Mississippi Half Step-> Big River, Tennessee Jed, The Music Never Stopped

Set 2

Terrapin Station-> Samson & Delilah, Friend Of The Devil, Estimated Prophet, Eyes Of The World-> Drums-> The Wheel-> Wharf Rat-> Around & Around, E: U.S. Blues

reviews.review_text: Awesome!!! Been waiting for someone to do a Matrix of this show. As expected, turned out very well, especially considering the AUD of the show isn't the best quality. Little else to write about the amazing performance on this night. I'll just say that it's great to hear it in a new light as on here. Thanks to dusborne for taking the time to make it!!!

And The Winner Is... This one.

Dusborne has produced an outstanding example of how good a matrix can me.  Has all the clarity from the SBD with just enough of the AUD to really fill out the sound.  Phil is a beast throughout this one.

Thanks for the exceptional work and I look forward to your next work.
- Another excellent one, and much superior to the Barton Hall show despite the latter's reputation.

Might As Well Let's stop debating which show from this month was the best ever.

Might As Well enjoy 'em all, and just "smile, smile, smile."

Might as well, might as well.....

a rare and different tune set 1 has an unbelievable energy throughout, building in a crescendo and culminating with the incredible minglewood > 1/2 step > big river > jed > tmns finish.

second set is simply sublime from the opening notes to the closing.

the entire show is worthy of being discussed in the "greatest of all time" category.

Bertha I'm NOT going to debate & say that show was better than this show....blah, blah, blah. But the one thing I will say is the version of "Bertha" on here to open the first set is definitely one of my favorites! I will also go far enough to say that I thought it kinda out of the ordinary to open the second set with "Terrapin" but I guess at the time it was new and hadn't been put in the latter part if the 2nd set yet.  AND BTW HAPPY BIRTHDAY BILL!!!!!🌈🎵🎶🎶🎵🎵🎶🎶💞🌈✌💫💥👏👏

P/S It would be much better to be able to write the review WHILE BEING ABLE TO LISTEN AT THE SAME TIME. I'M ALWAYS SO EAGER TO GET BACK TO LISTENING THAT MY THOUGHTS ABOUT WHAT I WANT TO SAY GET JUMBLED. JERRY DIED IN 1995 and although some of his may be better than others Jerry had a flare for NOT PLAYING SONGS the SAME WAY!! AND SOME OF HIS IMPROVISATIONS WERE BETTER THAN OTHERS. BUT if Jerry was on stage it was a good night to be in the audience!!! IMHO JERRY GARCIA NOT ONLY SURPASSED JIMI HENDRIX IN HIS ABILITY TO PLAY LEAD GUITAR BUT HIS ABILITY AS A MUSICIAN TO MAKE THE AUDIENCE FEEL ONE WAY OR ANOTHER ACCORDING TO THE SONG HE WAS PLAYING SHOWED A MASSIVE CAPABILITY IN HIS ART THAT IS UNSURPASSED BY MOST MUSICIANs THAT I KNOW ABOUT. 
And I would also like to add that I was 9 years old  when these concerts were played & I'm jealous of everyone that was there on these tours or those that were even able to catch just one of these shows! Wow, the guys were sounding so good during these shows.
and he's buried in the Louisiana country-o  my favorite dead show.  first discovered it 10 years ago, on the deadpod, when i was in college.  never saw jerry live, only heard him.

Best Sound Quality for this gem!!! The betty board has been around for decades, and it is excellent. There is also a very nice AUD. But this Matrix just nails it.

There are parts of this show that are incomparable. There are parts of 5/8/77 that are incomparable. 5/9/77 is a step below as the energy just plumets after Good Lovin and they don't really get back on track until Comes a Time. Regardless, all 3 shows are seriously loaded. Each features several versions of songs that are among the very best they ever played.

5/7/77 has one, for sure, that is a hands down #1. This half-step takes the cake. It is the GOAT. There are lots of great versions and more than a few epic ones. 11/5/77 could offer legit competition if they hadn't sort of phoned in the post rio grande jam. This version has monster jam both before and after. The Big River is also a total smoke show and the mini sequence from Half-Step to the end of the set is just fun. 

The 2nd set is also stellar, though I wouldn't put any of it in all-time discussions(as a whole is an all-timer) until you get to Wharf Rat. I mean holy crap. Talk about bringing down the house. This is an easy 5 for sound, 5 for playing.
